sentences: In 1960, he moved to Chicago, Illinois, where he adopted the stage name Lonnie Brooks (Luther Johnson was already using the name Guitar Junior there).
In 1961, he played guitar on the double album Jimmy Reed at Carnegie Hall.
In 1969, he recorded his first album, Broke an’ Hungry, for Capitol Records.
In 1974, Brooks participated in a multi-artist tour of Europe and recorded an album, Sweet Home Chicago, for the French label Black & Blue.
In 1978, Iglauer included four of Brooks’s songs (including three originals) in the anthology series Living Chicago Blues, released by Alligator.
The album won the Grand Prix du Disque Award from the 1980 Montreux Jazz Festival.
His next album, Hot Shot, was released in 1983.
His album Wound Up Tight, released in 1986, featured his most famous fan, Johnny Winter, on guitar.
In 1987, BBC Radio broadcast an hour-long live performance by him.

Brooks’s 1991 release, Satisfaction Guaranteed, received much coverage in the press, including features and articles in the Washington Post, the Village Voice, the Chicago Tribune, the Los Angeles Times, Guitar World, Living Blues, Blues Revue, and other publications.
Brooks went on a national concert tour with B.B. King, Buddy Guy, Koko Taylor, Junior Wells and Eric Johnson in the summer of 1993.
In 1996, Brooks released Roadhouse Rules.
With fellow Gulf Coast blues veterans Long John Hunter and Phillip Walker (both of whom he had known and played with in the 1950s in Port Arthur), Brooks released Lone Star Shootout in 1999.
With fellow Gulf Coast blues veterans Long John Hunter and Phillip Walker (both of whom he had known and played with in the 1950s in Port Arthur), Brooks released Lone Star Shootout in 1999.
Besides his live and recorded performances, Brooks appeared in the films Blues Brothers 2000 and The Express: The Ernie Davis Story and in two UK television commercials for Heineken beer.
Brooks died in Chicago, Illinois, United States, on April 1, 2017, at the age of 83.
On June 25, 2019, The New York Times Magazine listed Lonnie Brooks among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the 2008 Universal fire.

Brooks co-authored the 1998 book Blues for Dummies, with Wayne Baker Brooks and the music historian, guitarist, and songwriter Cub Koda.
As of 2018 it is still in print.

sentences: Lonnie Brooks (born Lee Baker Jr., December 18, 1933 – April 1, 2017) was an American blues singer and guitarist.
There he attracted the attention of Bruce Iglauer, the head of the fledgling Alligator Records, who had previously seen him at the Avenue Lounge on the city’s West Side.
Brooks signed a contract with the label, which released his album Bayou Lightning the following year.
A 1982 trip to Germany resulted in an hour-long live performance on German television.
